Title : Saraguro
Text : {{otheruses}}
'''Saraguro''' (also '''Sarakuru''') is the capital of [[Saraguro Canton]] in [[Loja Province]], [[Ecuador]]. Saraguro parish has an area of {{convert|74.14|sqkm|sqm}}. The population of the parish increased from 7,346 in 2001 to 9,045 in 2010.<ref>https://www.citypopulation.de/php/ecuador-parish-admin.php?adm1id=1111, accessed 22 Mar 2017</ref>  Saraguro town had a population of 3,124 in 2001 and 4,031 in 2010 and has an elevation of {{convert|2719|m|ft}}.<ref>https://www.citypopulation.de/php/ecuador-parish.php?cityid=111150, accessed 22 Mar 2017</ref>
{{Coord|-3.622343|-79.239557|display=title}}
[[File:Unterwegs nach Loja Ecuador408.JPG|thumb|250px|right|The main plaza in Saraguro.]]

The [[Saraguro people|Saraguro]] is an Indigenous people part of the Kichwa nation who inhabit the Southern Highlands in Ecuador. They are a major component of the population and culture of the town and canton of Saraguro, which other major group of inhabitants are ''mestizos''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Macas|first1=Luis|last2=Belote|first2=Linda|last3=Belote|first3=Jim|title=Millennial Ecuador: Critical Essays on Cultural Transformations and Social Dynamics|date=2003|pages=216â€“241|ref=belote}}</ref>. Their clothing is characterized in the men by the ponchos and white hats with black spots (at the moment, they used the hats with wide wing made of wool of sheep) and espadrilles; and in women by the anacos and shawls of the same color.

